===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/oʊkeɪ/||lang=en}}

===Etymology 1===
{{unk.|lang=en}}. Wikipedia lists {{w|List_of_proposed_etymologies_of_OK|several possibilities}}, of which the most widely-accepted is that it is an abbreviation of "oll korrect", a comical spelling of "[[all correct]]" which first appeared in print in ''The Boston Morning Post'' on March 23, 1839, as part of a fad for similar fanciful abbreviations in the United States during the late 1830s. The variant {{m|en|okeh}} (which see) is sometimes said to suggest a {{etyl|cho|-}} origin.

====Alternative forms====
* [[O.K.]], [[o.k.]], [[ok]], [[okay]]

